@Database CFG_BBSGlobal

@Index HBBS:Docs/Misc/Index.guide/MAIN

@Node Main "HBBS:BBSGlobal Config File"

  >> Quick Access Buttons @{" EDIT " system "run >nil: $HBBSEditor HBBS:Docs/Configuration/BBSGlobal.Guide $HBBSEditorParams"}

  HBBS:BBSGlobal < @{" ShowMe " system "run >nil: $HBBSEditor HBBS:BBSGlobal $HBBSEditorParams"}
  ==============

  Description:

  The HBBS:BBSGlobal file defines global and system settings for the BBS.

  Options:

  BBSName=<string>              @{" More... " link BBSName}
  BBSSerial=<alphanumeric>      @{" More... " link BBSSerial}
  BBSLocation=<string>          @{" More... " link BBSLocation}
  BBSCountry=<string>           @{" More... " link BBSCountry}
  BBSGroup_XX=<string>          @{" More... " link BBSGroup_XX}
  BBSNodes=<numeric>            @{" More... " link BBSNodes}

  SysopAccount=<string>         @{" More... " link SysopAccount}

  Drive_XX=<path>               @{" More... " link Drive_XX}

  BBSDrive=<path>               @{" More... " link BBSDrive}

  MinFreeSpace=<numeric>        @{" More... " link MinFreeSpace}
  NoFreeSpaceScript=<file>      @{" More... " link NoFreeSpaceScript}

  ButtonName_XX=<string>        @{" More... " link ButtonName_XX}
  ButtonCMD_XX=<string>         @{" More... " link ButtonCMD_XX}

  HideScreen=<boolean>          @{" More... " link HideScreen}

  ErrorLogFile=<file>           @{" More... " link ErrorLogFile}
  CallersLogFile=<file>         @{" More... " link CallersLogFile}

  LanguageName_XX=<string>      @{" More... " link LanguageName_XX}
  LanguageExtn_XX=<string>      @{" More... " link LanguageExtn_XX}

  EditorCMD=<string>            @{" More... " link EditorCMD}

  MinPasswordLength=<numeric>   @{" More... " link MinPasswordLength}
  MaxUsernameAttempts=<numeric> @{" More... " link MaxUsernameAttempts}
  MaxPasswordAttempts=<numeric> @{" More... " link MaxPasswordAttempts}

  CopyBufferSize=<numeric>      @{" More... " link CopyBufferSize}

  Door_Timeout=<numeric>        @{" More... " link Door_Timeout}

  LogConfig=<boolean>           @{" More... " link LogConfig}
  ConfigLogFile=<file>          @{" More... " link ConfigLogFile}

@EndNode

@Node BBSName "BBSName"

  BBSName=<string>

    E.G.

    BBSName="Utopia"

    No Default, Must Be Set!

    This option sets the name of the BBS!

@EndNode

@Node BBSSerial "BBSSerial"

  BBSSerial=<alphanumeric>

    E.G.

    BBSSerial=416APC3

    Default = 0

    This option sets the serial number of the BBS, if you are a registered
    user you should fill this in.  Otherwise leave it set to 0.

    Note: PLEASE don't enter a false serial number or "borrow" another sysop's
    serial number.  It DOES NOT AFFECT THE BBS IN ANY WAY WHATSOEVER if you
    leave this option at 0.

@EndNode

@Node BBSLocation "BBSLocation"

  BBSLocation=<string>

    E.G.

    BBSLocation="South UK"

    Default = "UnKnown"

    This option defines the BBS's geographical location.

@EndNode

@Node BBSCountry "BBSCountry"

  BBSCountry=<string>

    E.G.

    BBSCountry="UK"

    Default = "UnKnown"

    This options defines in what country the BBS is located

@EndNode

@Node BBSGroup_XX "BBSGroup_XX"

  BBSGroup_XX=<string>

    E.G.

    BBSGroup_1="CRoSSPOiNT"
    BBSGroup_2="Tension"
    BBSGroup_3="LSD"

    Default = "UnKnown"

    This lets you specify what scene groups are active on your bbs
    or that you have conferences for.

    It's primary use it to allow users access to things (files,
    messages, etc) based on what group they're in.  This is in
    addition to access levels.  So you could set up your system
    for group leaders with a higher access level than other
    group members.

@EndNode

@Node BBSNodes "BBSNodes"

  BBSNodes=<numeric>

    E.G.

    BBSNodes=2

    No Default, Must Be Set!

    Specifies how many nodes the system has,  you should have one node for each
    modem you are connecting to your computer and an extra local one for the
    sysop.

    Don't forget to create the correct directories in HBBS:Nodes

@EndNode

@Node SysopAccount "SysopAccount"

  SysopAccount=<string>

    E.G.

    SysopAccount="Hydra"

    Default = "Sysop"

    This option sets the name of the sysop, there should be a user account
    created with the same name as this option.

    You can also set this in NodeGlobal and NodeLocal files to have a different
    sysop for each node. (Door coders should be aware of this!)

@EndNode

@Node Drive_XX "Drive_XX"

  Drives_XX=<path>

    E.G.

    Drive_1=DH0:
    Drive_2=DH1:

    No Default, Must be set!

    These options are set so that the BBS can calculate how much free space
    there is for uploads.  Don't specify the same actual device more than
    once and don't specify assigns (only volume names or device names)
    otherwise the BBS will not be able to work out how much space there is
    correctly.

@EndNode

@Node BBSDrive "BBSDrive"

  BBSDrive=<path>

    E.G.

    BBSDrive=DH0:

    No Default, Must Be Set!

    This option tells the bbs what drive to use for calculating how much can
    be uploaded at any one time. (should be the same drive that the HBBS:
    assign point to.)

@EndNode

@Node MinFreeSpace "MinFreeSpace"

  MinFreeSpace=<numeric>

    E.G.

    MinFreeSpace=4096

    Default = 4096

    Should Be Specified In KBytes (so 4096 = 4MB)

    This Option tells the BBS how much free space there must be to allow a
    user to upload.  If there is less than this space on the @{"BBSDrive" link BBSDrive} then
    the system runs the script specified in @{"NoFreeSpaceScript" link NoFreeSpaceScript}

    Transfer protocol doors much check this after each file has been uploaded
    before allowing another file in a batch to be transferred.

@EndNode

@Node NoFreeSpaceScript "NoFreeSpaceScript"

  NoFreeSpaceScript=<file>

    E.G.

    NoFreeSpaceScript=HBBS:Scripts/NoFreeSpace.scr

    No Default, Need Not Be Set!

    If this option is set then the system runs the script specified when
    there is less disk space availiable on the @{"BBSDrive" link BBSDrive} than specified
    in @{"MinFreeSpace" link MinFreeSpace}

@EndNode

@Node ButtonName_XX "ButtonName_XX"

  ButtonName_XX=<string>

    E.G.

    ButtonName_1=Callers Log
    ButtonName_2=Amiga Files
    ButtonName_3=PC Files

    No Default, Need not be set.

    These options are a bit like the user buttons on /X's control panel, only problem
    with LamiExpress is that you can only have a few buttons.. So i thought hmm, how
    can we have it so that the user can have as many programmable buttons as they
    liked ?  And then i came up with the idea of using a listview gadget instead
    of buttons! So you scroll the listview to the "button" of your choice and double
    click it! Kewl Eh ?

    @{"ButtonName_XX" link ButtonName_XX} specifes the actual name that gets printed in the list view
    @{"ButtonCMD_XX" link ButtonCMD_XX} specifies the actual command to run...

    There must be the same amount of ButtonCMD_XX options as there are
    ButtonName_XX options.

@EndNode

@Node ButtonCMD_XX "ButtonCMD_XX"

  ButtonCMD_XX=<string>

    E.G.

    ButtonCMD_1=PPMore HBBS:Nodes/CallersLog
    ButtonCMD_2=TTX HBBS:Conferences/Amiga/FileLists/DIR1
    ButtonCMD_3=TTX HBBS:Conferences/PC/FileLists/DIR1

    No Default, need not be set, but if set then you must have a matching
    ButtonName_XX..

    These specify th actuall comands that get run when the sysop double clicks
    on a "button" (see @{"ButtonName_XX" link ButtonName_XX})

@EndNode

@Node HideScreen "HideScreen"

  HideScreen=<boolean>

    E.G.

    HideScreen=TRUE

    Default = FALSE

    This tells Control wether or not to bring it's screen to the front when it
    is started up.

@EndNode

@Node CallersLogFile "CallersLogFile"

  CallersLogFile=<file>

    E.G.

    CallersLogFile=HBBS:Logs/CallersLog

    Default = HBBS:Nodes/CallersLog

    This file allows you to change the path and filename of the callers log
    file.  if you like you can change all your log files to the same filename
    and have one big log file..

    All door programs should take note of the settings for log file,
    especialy doors that analyze log files like nukers.

@EndNode

@Node ErrorLogFile "ErrorLogFile"

  ErrorLogFile=<file>

    E.G.

    ErrorLogFile=HBBS:Logs/ErrorLog.TXT

    Default = HBBS:Logs/ErrorLog

    This file allows you to change the path and filename of the error log
    file.

    If you like you can change all your log files to the same filename
    and have one big log file, but log file analzers might have a hard time

@EndNode


@Node LanguageName_XX "LanguageName_XX"

  LanguageName_XX=<string>

    E.G.

    LanguageName_1=English
    LanguageName_2=German
    LanguageName_3=French

    No Default, MUST be set, must also be paired with a LanguageExtn_XX of
    the same number.

    These options define the languages of SCREENS that are availiable to
    the user, if there is more than one language then the user will be
    asked what language to use when the join the system and they will be
    able to change this from the user preferences door.

    The language ONLY applies to SPECIAL screens that are displayed by
    doors.

    You can do a really cool trick with this option that lets your users
    pick an ANSI style!

    If you have more than one language/style defined the system will look
    for a file with the language extension, if it can't find that file,
    and before it goes into the next directory that it has to search further
    down the HBBS tree, it will look for a file with the language extension
    of "_DEF.TXT" (A default, this can't be changed at the moment, e-mail
    me if you want to be able to change this!)

    So, take the following example:

    LanguageName_1=Style 1
    LanguageExtn_1=_Style1.TXT
    LanguageName_2=Style 2
    LanguageExtn_2=_Style2.TXT

    If you were logging out of node 1 and your language/style was set to "Style 2"
    the following screens would be searched for:

    HBBS:Nodes/Node1/Screens/Special/LogOff_Style2.TXT
    HBBS:Nodes/Node1/Screens/Special/LogOff_DEF.TXT
    HBBS:Screens/Special/LogOff_Style2.TXT
    HBBS:Screens/Special/LogOff_DEF.TXT

    Easy really...

    This allows you to create seperate screens for things that you want to be in
    different styles, and lets you have a default to drop back to!

    See Also:  @{"LanguageExtn_XX" link LanguageExtn_XX}

@EndNode

@Node LanguageExtn_XX "LanguageExtn_XX"

  LanguageExtn_XX=<string>

    E.G.

    LanguageExtn_1=TXT
    LanguageExtn_2=GER
    LanguageExtn_3=FRE

    No Default, MUST be set, must also be paired with a LanguageName_XX of
    the same number.

    Specifies the file extension that is added to a SPECIAL screen name.

    See @{"LanguageName_XX" link LanguageName_XX} for more details.

@EndNode

@Node EditorCMD "EditorCMD"

  EditorCMD=<string>

    E.G.

    EditorCMD=TTX {FILE} SCREEN @S@

    No Default, required

    This option is used when you click on buttons on hbbs that need a text
    editor to edit a file

    the string {FILE} will be replaced by HBBS by the actual name of the file
    that HBBS wants to edit.

    To test this click on Control's "Configure" button, and then on the
    "BBS Config" button.

@EndNode

@Node MinPasswordLength "MinPasswordLength"

  MinPasswordLength=<number>

    E.G.

    MinPasswordLength=4

    No Default, required

    Specifies the minimum amount of characters a user can use for thier
    login password.

    This may also be used by other program that require password (and
    should be).


@EndNode

@Node MaxUsernameAttempts "MaxUsernameAttempts"

  MaxUsernameAttempts=<number>

    E.G.

    MaxUsernameAttempts=3

    No Default, required

    Specifies the amount of attempts the user is allowed before they are
    logged of the system for entering incorrect usernames.


@EndNode

@Node MaxPasswordAttempts "MaxPasswordAttempts"

  MaxPasswordAttempts=<number>

    E.G.

    MaxPasswordAttempts=3

    No Default, required

    Maximum amount of tries the user can have to enter thier password.

@EndNode

@Node CopyBufferSize "CopyBufferSize"

  CopyBufferSize=<number>

    E.G.

    CopyBufferSize=3

    Default=32768

    Maxmimum size of buffer size to allocate when copying files from one
    location to another.. (the bigger the faster!)  just make sure you have lots
    of memory if you set this to a high value.
    If it can't allocate this much memory then it will keep halving the value
    until it can allocate it.

@EndNode

@Node Door_Timeout "Door_Timeout"

  Door_Timeout=<number>

    E.G.

    Door_Timeout=15

    Default=20

    The node program waits this many seconds for a door to load.
    Note: If you are running any other door then a HBBS normal door (i.e. a
    CLI door) then this is ignored and no timeout will occur.

    This is really just a safeguard in case the door programs hangs upon
    loading before it has initialised.

    If the door software fail's you'll still end up with a hung node
    (blame the door coder!)

@EndNode

@Node LogConfig "LogConfig"

  LogConfig=<boolean>

    E.G.

    LogConfig=TRUE

    Default=FALSE

    When this option is enables every single call from each part of the system
    that attempts to load/save or get settings from a config file to be logged
    in a file specified with @{"ConfigLogFile" link ConfigLogFile}.

    This option is incredibly usefull for finding out where things might be
    going wrong, what options you are missing and what new doors are up to!

    WARNING:

    Don't use this function lightly.  Just opening a node created a 30k text file!

@EndNode

@Node ConfigLogFile "ConfigLogFile"

  ConfigLogFile=<file>

    E.G.

    ConfigLogFile=T:Config.log

    Default=HBBS:Logs/ConfigFiles.log

    See @{"LogConfig" link LogCOnfig}

@EndNode


